<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 92 / Iraq bows to UN pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IRAQ yesterday averted its most serious clash with the United Nations since
the Gulf war by agreeing to allow inspectors to search its agriculture
ministry in Baghdad.
The agreement appeared to lift any immediate threat of western military
action against Iraq to enforce the terms of the Gulf war ceasefire.
But President George Bush branded Iraqi President Saddam Hussein 'a bully, a
dictator, a merchant of death' and warned that the world would not tolerate
further Iraqi defiance.
Mr Rolf Ekeus, the UN official overseeing the dismantling of Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction, is due to arrive in the Iraqi capital tomorrow
accompanied by a new UN inspection team headed by a German. The team was
appointed after discussions with the Iraqis at the weekend.
As a gesture to Baghdad, two American members of the team will not enter the
disputed ministry but will stay outside, sifting through any material their
colleagues take from inside.
Asked if the crisis was over, Mr Ekeus said: 'I feel the immediate problem
is now settled. I am convinced about that.'
Mr Abdul Amir al-Anbari, Iraq's ambassador to the UN, said the dispute had
been resolved to the 'mutual satisfaction' of the UN weapons inspection
commission and the Iraqi government.
In London, the Foreign Office said Iraq had seen sense in the face of
international resolve. Its 'blatant attempts' to flout the UN ceasefire
resolutions had failed.
Governor Bill Clinton of Arkansas, the Democratic challenger to Mr Bush in
the November presidential election, said the US and its allies should
continue to press Baghdad to comply fully with the terms of the Gulf war
ceasefire. The agreement yesterday was a 'good first step,' he said.
In his scathing remarks about the Baghdad regime, Mr Bush said the Iraqi
leader had lied about the extent of Iraq's weapons programmes. Its agreement
to give UN weapons inspectors access did not change that.
Asked about a proposed ultimatum threatening force against Iraq, Mr Bush
replied: 'I don't know that anything more is required at this minute.'
But 'the real test' of Mr Saddam's behaviour would come in Iraq's response
to future inspections, he said. 'Behaviour along the lines we have just
witnessed will not be tolerated.'
Over the past week the US, France and Britain have made increasingly overt
threats of military action against Iraq after the UN inspectors were barred.
The inspectors were forced to camp for 18 days outside the ministry
building, which they believed housed information on Iraq's missile
programme.
Mr Ekeus acknowledged a probability that during the stand-off the ministry
building had been 'effectively cleaned out'. But there might still be
material significant for UN inspectors, including some relating to missiles
and nuclear weapons.
Asked if Iraq's intransigence had thwarted UN efforts to eliminate its heavy
arms capability, he said: 'I think we have successfully identified existing
weapons and destroyed them.'
Even more important, he said, was that the Iraqi production capability had
been destroyed, and there was no possibility of a major new effort to
reconstruct the missile programme. He said that UN operations since the
ceasefire meant Iraq was no longer a 'threat through intimidation and
terror'. But it still had a formidable air force and a strong land force.
US officials warned earlier yesterday that the resolution of the inspection
crisis was only one element in a pattern of confrontation by Iraq.
Mr Richard Cheney, the US defence secretary, said that as well as giving
unrestricted access to UN inspectors, Iraq must:
Agree to the destruction of anything that supports a programme of weapons of
mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
Agree not to use military force to suppress Shia Moslems in the south.
Participate in the UN-sponsored commission to resolve the boundary dispute
with Kuwait.
Allow UN refugee and humanitarian officials to continue to have unimpeded
access to Iraq.
