<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 92 / Japan cuts discount rate by 1/2 point
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of Japan cut official interest rates early today in an admission
that the economy is in worse shape than it had previously conceded.
The central bank's decision to cut the official discount rate (ODR) from
3.75 per cent to 3.25 per cent was immediately welcomed by Mr Tsutomu Hata,
the finance minister, as 'a timely and appropriate step'.
The move had been awaited eagerly by the securities industry, which had
feared that the Tokyo stock market would continue to fall this week after
losing 3.4 per cent on Friday to close at a six-year low.
Share prices opened higher this morning after the cut, with the Nikkei
average up some 400 points, or 2 1/2 per cent, after an hour's trading. On
the Tokyo currency market, the dollar opened at Y127.63 against a New York
closing rate of Y128.1 on Friday.
Central bank officials said that the rate reduction would contribute to
realising stable domestic economic growth. Previously the bank had hoped
that the lowering of the ODR from 4.5 per cent on April 1 would be the last
cut for the year, but a quarterly forecast published last week recognised
that recovery would not, as predicted, come in the autumn.
After the deregulation of Japan's financial markets, the effects of an ODR
cut will be more symbolic than real, although it will encourage downward
movement in market rates. In recent days, the central bank had allowed
market rates to fall, heightening speculation that a cut was imminent.
The cut is certain to be widely interpreted as an attempt to bolster the
stock market, but Mr Yasushi Mieno, Bank of Japan governor, has previously
insisted that 'official interest rates are not reduced to support share
prices'. He is concerned that growth is being retarded by the 'pessimistic
mood' of Japanese consumers. The bank is also worried that pressure is
increasing on Japanese financial institutions, which are restructuring a
growing number of corporate clients exposed to the stock and property
markets, and unable to trade themselves out of trouble.
Japan is also under growing US pressure to meet the official 3.5 per cent
growth forecast for the year to end March 1993. That target now appears out
of reach, and private institutions are generally forecasting growth of
little more than 2 per cent for the year.
The slowdown has led to a surge in Japan's trade surplus - a record Dollars
49bn (Pounds 25bn) for the first half and still rising. The US and Japan
begin a two-day review tomorrow of a pact signed in 1990 to remove
'structural impediments' to bilateral trade, and the US is certain to ask
Tokyo to stimulate the economy.
LDP tightens grip, Page 3
Peace, prosperity and corruption, Page 34
</TEXT>
