<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 92 / International Company News: Earnings at Asarco in sharp
decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ASARCO, the US integrated mining company, reported second quarter net
earnings of Dollars 4.9m, or 12 cents per share, a sharp decline from the
Dollars 15.4m, or 37 cents per share, in the same period last year.
Lower metals prices and slack production at several key mines cut into
results. Sales were Dollars 487.2m for the second quarter, compared with
Dollars 458.9m last year.
Copper production at the company's Ray mine in Arizona was impeded by heavy
rains and at its Mission mine, also in Arizona, by lower grade and harder
ores. Lead and zinc production fell at its Missouri mines because of lower
ore grades.
In the three months ended June 30, the company's average realised price for
copper declined 2 cents to Dollars 1.03 a pound, 10 cents for silver to
Dollars 4.11 an ounce, and Dollars 29 for gold to Dollars 364 per ounce. The
average realised price for lead remained flat at 26 cents a pound, while
zinc rose rose 10 cents to 62 cents per pound.
Some of these adverse price and production effects were offset by a second
quarter Dollars 2.1m dividend from the Southern Peru Copper Corporation and
a credit of Dollars 3.4m from a settlement with Canadian tax authorities.
The 1991 second quarter had benefited from a Dollars 5.1m gain from the sale
of Asarco's shares in Highland Gold and a credit for capitalised interest
worth Dollars 2.1m more than in the 1992 period.
For the first six months, Asarco had net earnings of Dollars 11.8m, or 29
cents per share, on sales of Dollars 945m. For the same period last year,
net earnings were Dollars 23.4m, or 57 cents per share, on sales of Dollars
924.1m.
