<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Money Markets: Calm end to week
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Calm returned to both the sterling cash and futures markets yesterday after
the pound consolidated its position on the foreign exchanges and the Bank of
England was accomodating with a large shortage.
After a turbulent week in the cash markets, dominated by fears of an
imminent rise in Germany's Lombard rate, money market operators had a
relaxed day. Several of the German states released sharply reduced inflation
figures, suggesting that next week's German cost-of-living figure for July
will be down 1 per cent to 3.3 per cent. That eased fears of an interest
rate increase when the Bundesbank council meets on August 6.
Sterling also firmed on the foreign exchanges, rising more than 1 1/2
pfennigs. The Bank of England added to the cheer by being very accomodating
in its money market intervention, forecasting a shortage of Pounds 1.55bn
but inviting offers in the early round and having most of the shortage taken
out at that stage.
Period rates in the cash market, if not bullish, were at least a bit softer.
At the end of the day, 1 month money was offered  1/8 per cent cheaper from
its previous close, at 10 1/8 per cent. Three-month money was  1/16 per cent
softer at 10 5/16 per cent. There was also a slight softening at the long
end of the yield curve, with 1-year money dropping back to 10 1/4 per cent
from 10 3/8 per cent the night before.
Futures trading was easier. The September contract closed up 4 basis points
from its previous finish at 89.76. However, this was far from bullish,
bearing in mind that the September contract has been up at 90.25 since base
rates dropped to 10 per cent.
Both the futures and cash rates are still pricing in a  1/4 per cent rise in
base rate, and the mood in the market remains tense. But the feeling is
widespread that sterling may have a respite for the next few weeks.
In early operations, the Bank purchased Pounds 136m of Band 1 treasury
bills, Pounds 423m of Band 1 bank bills and Pounds 344m of Band 2 bank bills
at 9 7/8 per cent, and Pounds 400m in a repo repayable on 11 and 12 August
at 9 15/16 per cent. The shortage was later revised to Pounds 1.5bn. In the
afternoon, the Bank purchased Pounds 30m of Band 1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per
cent and provided late assistance of Pounds 90m.
</TEXT>
