<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / International Company News: Jefferson Smurfitt US interests
in refinancing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US interests of Jefferson Smurfit, which were the subject of a complex
Dollars 2.9bn leveraged buy-out in 1989, are being refinanced via a Dollars
400m equity investment.
Jefferson, the large Irish paper and packaging group, combined its main US
paper and paperboard interests in a highly leveraged deal three years ago.
This deal involved the acquisition of Container Corporation of America
(CCA), a paperboard company Jefferson had bought in the mid-1980s, and
Jefferson Smurfit Corporation (JSC), its St Louis-based subsidiary, by a
leveraged buy-out vehicle called SIBV/MS Holdings.
SIBV/MS Holdings, in turn, was - and is - 50 per cent cent-owned by
Jefferson Smurfit, and 50 per cent by an investor group led by Morgan
Stanley, the US investment bank. The LBO deal netted Jefferson Smurfit some
Dollars 1bn in cash, and transformed its balance sheet.
According to yesterday's announcement, 'certain' existing shareholders in
JSC and CCA have agreed on the principal terms of new Dollars 400m equity
investment in the US operation. The investment will be made partly in cash,
and partly via the conversion next year of JSC's outstanding preferred
stock.
About Dollars 200m of JSC's subordinated debt will be bought back at a
premium, and new Dollars 400m bank facility, underwritten by Chemical Bank
and Bankers Trust, will be provided. Proceeds of that facility will be used
to prepay part of the US operations' present bank facility.
JSC confirmed that Jefferson Smurfit will put up its full Dollars 200m share
of the equity investment. However, because it owns all the outstanding
preferred stock which will convert, its cash commitment will be only
approximately Dollars 35m.
Completion of the deal is subject to the negotiation of a definitive
agreement.
</TEXT>
