<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Unit trust funds drop to Pounds 57bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FUNDS under management in unit trusts dropped last month to Pounds 57bn
after breaking the Pounds 60bn barrier in May.
This was in spite of an increase in net sales of unit trust personal equity
plans (Peps) to Pounds 336.4m in the second quarter, pushing the value of
unit trust Pep funds over the Pounds 2bn mark to Pounds 2.4bn.
But unit trusts last month experienced their first outflow since February,
with sales exceeding purchases by Pounds 23.5m. Total sales last month were
Pounds 617.4m, a big drop on the previous month and on the Pounds 1bn
achieved in April.
However, net inflows in the second quarter of the year, at Pounds 463.8m,
far exceeded the Pounds 255.8m achieved in the first quarter and represented
one of the highest quarterly sales since 1989.
Inflows into unit trust Peps were aided in the second quarter by the change
to Pep rules in the Budget. Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, announced that
Pounds 6,000 could be invested in a unit or investment trust Pep from the
start of the 1992-93 tax year. The previous limit had been Pounds 3,000.
Mr Philip Warland, director-general of the Unit Trust Association said: 'The
sales of Peps are a quite remarkable achievement in a personal savings
market which saw outflows from building societies and the great attraction
of National Savings.'
</TEXT>
