<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Judge blocks Lonrho action
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ACTION for damages in the High Court by Lonrho, the international trading
group, and Mr Tiny Rowland, its chief executive, was yesterday ordered to be
struck out. The action alleged a 'dirty tricks' campaign by the Fayed
brothers during the row over the ownership of Harrods, the London department
store,
'I fail to see why such a public, unpleasant and vitriolic vendetta should
be allowed to be aired in court,' Mr Justice Macpherson said. He described
the action, launched last year, as another round in the 'prolonged public
warfare with no holds barred' over the Fayeds' acquisition of the House of
Fraser stores group.
If the action were allowed to go ahead it would inevitably involve raking
over the whole dispute with 'mud slung in all directions', the judge added.
Lonrho and Mr Rowland were ordered to pay the costs of House of Fraser's
application to have the action struck out. Lonrho was refused leave to
appeal but its lawyers said later there were good grounds for appeal and
that further moves would be considered.
The action sought damages and an injunction in respect of an alleged
conspiracy by brothers Mr Mohammed and Mr Ali Fayed to injure Lonrho and Mr
Rowland.
The judge said that, over the past six years, Lonrho and Mr Rowland had been
intent on discrediting the Fayeds and had spared no expense. But the Fayeds
themselves were not 'lily white' and were prepared to 'descend to the depths
of vulgarity'.
The judge said he was 'sceptical' of Lonrho's claim for damages and 'even
more sceptical' of its claim for an injunction. Neither remedy was likely to
be available to the company.
</TEXT>
