<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Debate by Labour to focus on structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN a third of the 459 resolutions tabled for Labour's annual
conference focus on the party's organisation and administration, it emerged
yesterday.
The concentration on internal affairs, taking up 154 resolutions, is a
direct consequence of the post mortem now under way on why the party
suffered such a heavy defeat in the general election. Policy issues are less
heavily discussed.
But the resolution document, published yesterday, also shows evidence of the
predominance of advocates of party modernisation and their determination to
push ahead with further changes.
As promised, the AEEU, the union formed by the merger of the EETPU
electricians' union with the AEU engineering union, has tabled a motion
demanding the immediate introduction of a one-member, one-vote system for
the selection of party candidates.
Other features of the document are a newly emphatic stress on the importance
of 'green' issues and a lengthy section on the media, with many resolutions
urging the party to adopt new techniques such as telephone canvassing aimed
at 'bypassing' Conservative-dominated newspapers.
While there are still many clearly leftwing motions, there are also several
suggesting that Labour must move further towards the Conservatives, with one
suggesting that opposition to compulsory competitive tendering must be
dropped.
</TEXT>
