<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Complaints made about adverts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Advertising Standards Authority said yesterday that it started receiving
complaints from the public about Land Travel in 1988. Most of the complaints
concerned advertisements in the regional press and in brochures in travel
agencies.
Ms Caroline Crawford of the authority said: 'There have not been a massive
amount of complaints but over the last 12 months we have published five
reports on Land Travel, upholding complaints - which is above average for a
travel company.'
The authority has one complaint against Land Travel still under
consideration. All complaints against the company to the authority have been
upheld.
The main complaints concerned the company's alleged failure to abide by
stated tour itineraries. For instance, one trip to Czechoslovakia and
Austria allegedly listed visits to Prague, Krakow and mountain castles but
did not go to any of those places.
Another trip, a coach tour to the Rhineland, said 'go and see Cologne's
beautiful cathedral' but the coach allegedly drove straight through Cologne
without stopping.
Ms Crawford said: 'We found that Land Travel did in fact amend
advertisements when we asked them but they were perhaps not careful enough
that, at the time of going to press, their advertised itineraries were
accurate.'
The authority can issue warnings to the media which go to all advertising
sales departments, requesting the media to seek its advice before accepting
advertisements from troublesome companies.
However, the authority does not disclose whether or not it takes such action
against particular companies.
A further sanction which the authority can invoke is a referral to the
Office of Fair Trading - however there was no such referral in the case of
Land Travel.
</TEXT>
