<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Council and UN chief make peace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A ROW between the United Nations Security Council and Mr Boutros Boutros
Ghali, the secretary-general, over peacekeeping in Bosnia-Hercegovina was
resolved last night after long private consultations.
Having decided a week ago that the UN should supervise the collection of
heavy weapons from each side in the Bosnian conflict, the council accepted
Mr Boutros Ghali's objections that conditions did not yet exist for the
operation.
The council invited him to contact all member states, particularly in
Europe, to get personnel, equipment and logistic support for such an
operation. He could then undertake 'the further preparatory work needed' for
the supervision.
The EC has also been invited to co-operate more closely with the
secretary-general in an effort to resolve the Yugoslav conflict. In a report
to the council on Wednesday he said the supervision plan approved in the
recent London agreement had been adopted without consulting him and that, in
effect, the EC tail was trying to wag the UN dog.
The Community has been asked to consider broadening and intensifying the
conference on Yugoslavia to help the search for peace.
A UN recovery team yesterday reached a UN relief convoy which was stranded
for 24 hours in a Bosnian minefield and both were on the move to safety,
officials told Reuter in Sarajevo.
