FT  25 JUL 92 / France sees its trade slip into deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE slipped into a trading deficit of FFr951m (Pounds 97m) last month
after five months of trade surpluses, writes Alice Rawsthorn. So far this
year French companies have benefited from buoyant exports which have helped
to shelter them from the sluggish state of the domestic market.
The value of French exports rose to FFr106.4bn last month from FFr103.4bn in
May. However imports rose at a faster rate to FFr107.4bn in June from
FFr99.3bn in the preceding month thereby pushing the trade account into the
red.
Despite last month's deficit, France recorded a healthy trading surplus of
FFr16.6bn in the first half of this year.
