<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Iraq military sites 'poor target'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEMOLITION of Iraq's military sites since the end of the Gulf war has
been so great that they are not worthwhile targets for any military action
by the United Nations, according to Mr David Kay, former head of one of the
UN inspection teams in Iraq.
Mr Kay said last night that almost all the installations in Iraq's huge
secret nuclear weapons programme had been demolished by UN teams. Last
September, in an episode that foreshadowed this month's impasse outside the
Agriculture Ministry, his team camped for five days in the car park of the
Baghdad Defence Ministry until they were allowed to take away documents.
Al-Tuwaitha, the main nuclear research centre south of Baghdad 'has been
taken to bits' and al-Atheer, the main weapons design and testing centre,
'has now completely gone', he said.
Al-Shakat and Tarmiya, two sites north of Baghdad used to produce enriched
uranium, necessary for nuclear weapons, had also been demolished, and there
was one building left at al-Farat, which had produced enrichment equipment.
UN inspectors, who were astonished at the scale of the nuclear research
programme they uncovered, concluded that Iraq could have been within a year
of producing a weapon when the war started. There is no evidence that it had
yet built a workable weapon.
Mr Kay, who is now director-general of the Uranium Institute in London, said
he did not believe the UN would target chemical weapons sites around Mosul
in the north of the country in any strike as they were due to be dismantled
anyway in September.
'The weapons there are already leaking, there is already a risk to the
inspectors, and if they bombed those sites no-one could go near them.'
However, he said that industrial and military installations around Tikrit,
President Saddam Hussein's home town north-west of Baghdad, might still be
considered a target, and that there was still a large military base around
Falluja, west of Baghdad.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
