FT  25 JUL 92 / Banks at odds in Bombay scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A WRANGLE broke out yesterday between Citibank and Standard Chartered in the
latest twist in Bombay's Rs35bn (Pounds 625m) financial scandal.
Standard Chartered has sent a written demand through its solicitors to
Citibank in Bombay, claiming that the American bank owes it more than Rs900m
over two securities transactions. Informal talks between the two banks have
failed to resolve the issue.
Citibank claimed yesterday it 'did not owe Standard Chartered anything' and
was not the only bank to have received such letters from Standard Chartered.
A Citibank vice-president in Bombay said it had proof that it had cleared
all dues pertaining to the two transactions cited in the letter  - one
relating to the sale of bonds issued by the government-owned Indian Railway
Finance Corporation, the other to government bonds.
A Standard Chartered spokesman said 'there were numerous grey areas' between
the banks. However, he insisted 'there has been a warm sense of co-operation
between the foreign banks' since the financial scandal broke, and said that
'no court case had yet been initiated' on any transaction.
The scandal, which emanated from the market for bankers' receipts, has
proved a serious embarrassment to the Indian government.
India's leading foreign banks were thrust to the forefront of the affair
earlier this month when a central bank report claimed that controversial
securities market trading had been concentrated in their hands and in those
of four brokers now under arrest.
The central bank ordered a special audit of Citibank, Standard Chartered,
Bank of America and ANZ Grindlays.
