<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Iraq may yield to UN probe: Military strike threatened
unless Baghdad allows weapons inspection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS at the UN and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRAQ made a conciliatory gesture in its tussle with the United Nations over
weapons inspections last night, as the US, Britain and France were on the
verge of giving Baghdad an ultimatum threatening military action.
Iraq's UN ambassador said he 'got the impression' Baghdad would give a 'very
positive' response today to compromise proposals from the UN on how to carry
out the inspections.
The apparent climb-down came as the western powers prepared a formal
ultimatum, warning that Iraq faces a military strike unless it allows UN
inspectors access to its weapons of mass destruction programme.
Baghdad has been refusing to let an inspection team into an agriculture
ministry building which the UN believes has documents about Iraq's nuclear
programme and possibly about chemical weapons.
As the crisis neared a climax, President George Bush yesterday cancelled
plans to be away from Washington at the weekend. He had planned to stay at
his holiday home in Kennebunkport, Maine. But instead he will meet top
national security advisers today at the presidential retreat of Camp David,
near Washington.
US officials earlier confirmed that the ultimatum - possibly issued in the
name of the UN secretary-general or Security Council but open to others to
join - might come this weekend and could require Iraqi compliance within a
matter of days.
Though confirming moves to draw up an ultimatum, British officials in London
warned against assuming that military action was a foregone conclusion. They
felt there was a reasonable chance President Saddam Hussein would 'blink'
once he understood the western powers were serious in threatening force.
Mr Rolf Ekeus, head of the UN inspection commission, appeared hopeful last
night the crisis might be resolved without military measures, following two
rounds of talks in New York with Dr Abdul Amir al-Anbari, the Iraqi delegate
to the UN.
Apparently signalling a shift in attitudes, Mr al-Anbari said: 'My feeling
is that the crisis will be solved in a satisfactory way - to the
satisfaction of the UN and the Iraqi government.' After speaking by
telephone to an unnamed minister in Baghdad, he said he would have Iraq's
response by today to proposals put by Mr Ekeus. 'I got the impression that
will be very positive,' he said.
Military contingency plans are a close secret, but it is assumed US, British
and French aircraft would lead any renewed bombing of Iraqi targets. The
Pentagon said there were 21,000 US servicemen in the Gulf area, mostly
aboard 17 warships.
Military sites poor target, Page 2
</TEXT>
