</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Arts: The Sun that never sets - Records
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARRY BOOTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST BEFORE Sun Ra and his Solar Myth Arkestra arrived at the Brecon Jazz
Festival, to no-one's surprise, a wizard occupied the centre aisle of the
market hall venue - crescents, goatee, aromatherapy tackle and all - to
await an old man who claims to be from Saturn.
Ra and his Arkestra, with imagery which combines Eygptology with pulp
sci-fi, has always attracted a jolly lunatic fringe. But his wide ranging
writing and arrangements, which mix big band grandeur with quirky and often
free improvisation, could command universal appeal.
A dearth of easily available recorded material has helped keep Sun Ra in the
cult category, however, and until recently his records, many of them
released in small numbers on his own Saturn label, were stricly for
aficionados or collectors. With Ra in the twilight of his career the
situation has been rectified with the release of a series of CDs from
Pennslyvania-based Evidence Music Inc and another from Black Saint, Mayan
Temples.
The five Evidence albums are cleaned up reissues of Ra's own creaky Saturn
recordings from the early Fifties into the Sixties, with original liner
illustration, good notes and pyschedelically embossed discs. Mayan Temples,
recorded only two years ago and covering more recent material, provides the
other bookend to a long career.
Although he denies it now, he started out as Sonny Blount, born sometime
around 1910 in Birmingham, Alabama. He worked his way north, via the
southern circuit, to Chicago where, at the Club DeLisa, he met big band
leader Fletcher Henderson. Usually cited as Ra's major influence, Fletcher
Henderson employed him as pianist and arranger for only two years (1947 -
49) before Ra's own writing and space age pre-occupations began to evolve,
first with a trio and eventually with 12 pieces. The Arkestra, often with
the same personnel for years on end, has been in colourful orbit ever since.
At an Arkestra show Ra's cosmic cadets fill the stage, a constellation of
brass, lurex and sequins. Old hands tenorist John Gilmore and altoist
Marshall Allen have blasted off alongside alumni such as Clifford Jarvis,
Julian Priester and Pharoah Sanders in their time. The leader, stately but
fragile after a stroke in 1990, is wrapped in tinsel and half carried to the
front of the stage by two acolytes. Between thoughtfully placed chunks of
chords he peers wistfully through watery eyes across synth and piano
keyboards as younger members of the ensemble turn cartwheels.
If the show is out of this world so is the music and the new Evidence discs
do it justice, covering a period when Ra's ideas and influences were
gelling. Sound Sun Pleasure (ECD 22013), for example, contains what are said
to be Ra's first ever seven sides, when the band was the Astro-Infinity
Arkestra, and they range from the Gershwins' 'S'Wonderful' to the corn of a
crooning 'Dreams Come True'.
Five cracking discs are available from Evidence, including Monorails and
Satellites, a solo outing for Ra at piano, and five more from the Saturn
catalogue are due in October.
Holiday for Soul Dance (ECD22011), Jazz In Silhouette (ECD 22012), Monorails
And Satellites (ECD22013), Sound Sun Pleasure (ECD 22014), Supersonic Jazz
(ECD 22015) are on the Evidence label. Mayan Temples (120121-2) is on Black
Saint. All are available from distributors Harmonia Mundi in London (Tel:
071-253-0863).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-11223</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGYAKAEGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920725
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Arts: Shades of the past - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
OSCAR WILDE always knew better than he wrote. Now he has posthumously
pronounced on Sharman Macdonald's new play, Shades, at the Albery Theatre:
'All women become like their mothers. That is their tragedy. No man does.
That's his.' Shades is a tragicomedy about a woman, her son, and her mother.
It makes slow-paced, unusual drama, boldly conceived and well acted, but
strangely unaffecting.
Pearl (wonderfully played by Pauline Collins) is a 42-year-old widow,
trapped between her cossetted son and her stern mother. The action is set in
1950s Glasgow during a night out with her beau, Callum.
The play rests on the over-close relationship between Pearl and her
ten-year-old son (well played by Matthew Steer). She has ambitions for him
and has made sacrifices: 'We could have a better life if I didn't pay for
your education.' But she will not let him go. She looks elsewhere for
security. After dancing with Callum (James Cosmo), Pearl proposes marriage.
He rejects her. She returns home to her mother, a matter-of-fact
Presbyterian, and to her bedwetting son.
The action has an appropriate claustrophobia, aided by Christopher Morley's
gloomy design. Simon Callow's direction slows it to a flat sameness:
fastening a dress, putting on a jacket, folding a bow tie, are deliberate
significant acts.
The shades of the title refer to the dark interiors of Pearl's home and to
the ghost of her husband. A brighter elsewhere appears in memories of
Pearl's happily married past, of VJ Day: 'We went to bed, and for joy, we
made a baby.'
The play's weakness is that it gestures to the past instead of showing the
present. Shakespeare or Chekhov give sufficient information so that their
characters become explicable; rather than probing back in time, they show
the action advancing. The problem with Shades is its refusal to show rather
than tell.
The play's strength lies in its subject, ideal for Collins' talents: a woman
on the threshold of middle age trapped between an idyllic past and a
daunting future, holding on to a son who will move from one to the other in
leaving her. It would make a good short story in its present form. Growing
old alone is usually the literary province of men; Kafka said it best 80
years ago: 'It seems so dreadful to stay a bachelor . . . always having to
say good night at the front door, never to run up a stairway beside one's
wife, to have only side-doors in one's room leading into other people's
living-rooms.' Shades puts the woman's view.
For a limited season at The Albery Theatre (071-867-1115).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
