<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Survey of Second Cars (4): Tempting offers - at a price -
Ways to Finance / 'Free credit' is genuinely available but it usually has a
price-tag
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BORROWING money to buy an asset which depreciates as fast as a car is
inadvisable. Adding to your personal debt burden, even minimally, to acquire
a second car seems ludicrous.
Gone are the go-go 1980s. These are the caring 1990s when experts are
advising us to pay off our debts as quickly as possible - even the mortgages
on our houses - because we are unlikely to receive a return on savings
higher than the rate we have to pay on money we borrow.
So obviously the best way to finance the purchase of a second car is either
to pay cash from savings or to save until the cash is available.
For those people who for some reason cannot follow this advice, a loan
arranged by the dealer selling the car might well be the cheapest form of
finance. Most car companies have their own finance subsidiaries and these
may offer very attractive terms.
Dealer finance rates are often negotiable. If you don't like the sound of
the first offer, find out elsewhere if better terms are available.
Personal loans from banks or building societies - organisations also geared
up to deal with individuals seeking money - are also likely to offer
competitive terms.
But shop around by checking the APR (annual percentage rate) on loans,
remembering that APR often varies according to the length of loan. Don't
forget to see if you qualify for some special deal because you work for a
particular company or belong to a particular trade union or other
organisation. Gold credit card holders are offered special, low rates on
loans.
Hire purchase arrangements tend to be more expensive than bank and building
society loans and in some circumstances you can lose the car if you fail to
keep up with the payments. On the other hand, with hire purchase you are
better protected if something goes wrong with the car because the hire
purchase provider has joint liability. For instance, if the dealer went
bankrupt and could not fulfil his obligations you would still be legally
protected by the finance company.
On this question of protection, some lenders sell their own insurance
policies to ensure the loan is repaid should something go terribly wrong
with your health or job. However, these can be very expensive - some even
add about 30 per cent to the cost of the loan.
It is sometimes possible to link a loan for a car to an existing property
mortgage. The interest is likely to be favourable but many people would not
think it worth repaying a car loan for the rest of the mortgage term. This
cash-raising option probably would suit only those with mortgages with
relatively little time still to run.
At the other extreme, if you need to raise a short-term loan for a car
(perhaps while waiting for some savings which are taking time to release) an
overdraft from your friendly bank manager will almost certainly be the
cheapest form of finance.
As there is no conclusive indication yet that the car market is moving out
of recession, there is a proliferation of tempting offers by manufacturers
and dealers.
Free credit is genuinely available but it usually has its price.
Interest-free credit is generally offered only if you pay the full retail
price for a car, whereas a cash buyer can often get a reasonable discount.
Interest-free credit is frequently on offer only if the loan is paid back
quickly. For example, there is a zero interest rate with Vauxhall's current
deal on Novas and Cavaliers - but only if you put down a 50 per cent deposit
and pay the remainder back in one year.
If you decide to try to negotiate a discount for cash (with perhaps the
intention of raising a personal loan to cover the outlay) it is best to
remember that the average dealer's profit margin on high-volume, small cars
is about 18 per cent. However, manufacturers frequently set dealers agreed
sales targets which, when reached, can earn the dealer an additional credit
of 3 or 4 per cent off every car sold during the offer period - which might
be over several months.
Consequently, if you are lucky enough to catch a dealer who is only a few
units short of the sales target with just a few days to go, you might strike
a very good bargain indeed.
One sign that these are difficult times for car producers is an unusual
scheme that Ford, the market leader in the UK, has introduced. Ford has come
up with what is virtually a car leasing scheme for private individuals and
it must be assumed that its rivals will follow suit if it shows any sign of
success.
With Ford's 'Options' scheme, a customer chooses a new car and the
manufacturer guarantees the value at the end of the finance agreement by
advising, in writing, the car's minimum guaranteed future value - Ford's
estimate of the amount the car might be worth at the end of the agreement.
This sum is then deducted from the price of the car so that the customer
makes payments only on the balance, plus interest on the full price.
At the end of the agreement customers have three options:
Choose a new car, selling the old car themselves or through the dealers'
resale club. The guaranteed future value amount is only paid to Ford Credit.
In this situation the customer benefits from any profit above the guaranteed
future value.
Keep the car by paying the guaranteed future value amount.
Return the car to the dealer.
Mr Ian McAllister, chairman of Ford of Britain, suggests that Options will
make a new car 'affordable' for many people who, because of the recession,
have been unable to buy one. He says Options aims 'to encourage customer
loyalty and to enable customers to change their cars more frequently with
minimal change to their monthly budget'.
Anyone who has tried to sell a used car recently will tell you that Options
looks like a good deal. However, there are some drawbacks. For example, you
might not actually receive the guaranteed future value payment you expected
if the car has suffered excess wear and tear. Ford dealers will apply the
same scale used for measuring damage to leased cars to assess the reduction
in value and the buyer will have to make up any shortfall.
Also, where the car is sold through a dealer for more than the guaranteed
value, the dealer may insist on a share of the profit.
But whatever method you choose to finance that second car, remember the
golden rule: never borrow more money than you can raise if you have to sell
the car in a hurry.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
