<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / Survey of Second Cars (1): Expectations are rising - Two-car
households are already commonplace in Britain. Furthermore, a growing number
expect to acquire a second - or a third - car by the end of next year,
indicating a willingness to look beyond the recession to more prosperous
times
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUDGING by the statistical evidence, there is a dispiriting task ahead for
environmentalists and traffic planners seeking to persuade motorists out of
their cars and on to public transport.
The upgrading of public transport networks for commuters and city centre
bans on cars to ease congestion and pollution are expected to provide some
partial victories.
But net growth of the car population for the forseeable future seems
inevitable as the result of increasing prosperity (current recession
notwithstanding), the decline of bus and rail services in rural areas, more
women at work and other social factors - not least the advent of the 'school
run' as parents grow increasingly unwilling to allow their children to cycle
or otherwise travel alone.
Already, in the UK, there are just under 400 cars per 1,000 population,
according to statistics from government departments and the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders. Over the past 11 years, the UK's population has
risen by two per cent to reach 57.6m last year, the number of households has
grown by 11 per cent - and the number of cars by 28 per cent, to 22.6m.
As this year's Lex Report on Motoring* found, in a survey conducted with the
MORI polling organisation, the two-car household is already a commonplace.
Thirty-four per cent of the 1,277 households surveyed for the report had two
cars, six per cent had three, and two per cent four or more.
For car makers and dealers, however, it was the attitudes and expectations
of the households surveyed that made the most interesting - and from their
viewpoint, encouraging - reading:
Of households with at least one car, 15 per cent expected to have acquired a
second, third or fourth car by the end of next year. Only 7 per cent
expected to give one up. Intriguingly, the proportion expecting to acquire
an additional car was higher than in the previous year's survey, indicating
a willingness to look beyond the recession towards more prosperous times.
The Lex/MORI research indicated that of the additional 1.6m cars expected to
take to the UK's roads between the beginning of this year and the end of
next - after allowing for scrappage of existing ones - around one-half will
be 'second' cars.
Just over 80 per cent of these are expected to be used vehicles. But that
still leaves some 100,000 purchases of new 'second' cars a year - a valuable
market for the trade and industry, particularly at a time when the overall
new car market remains severely depressed.
Not suprisingly, however, second (or third, or fourth) car sales are
concentrated at the lower end of the price spectrum, reflecting the use of
most of them as runabouts.
The Volkswagen group's own regular new car buyers survey illustrates the
point. Last year, 45.5 per cent of its Polo small hatchback sales were
identified as being not the main car in a household (the small hatchback
average is just under 40 per cent). The percentage slipped to 23.8 per cent
in the case of the Golf, and to just under 4 per cent for larger and more
expensive cars like the Passat and Audi 80.
A much smaller proportion is of more specialised vehicles, such as 'leisure'
four-wheel-drive vehicles bought for their 'image' - many of which will
never stray from the highway - or sports cars, now a rapidly reviving
sector.
The reason usually identified by surveys as the most common one for
acquiring an extra car is of least immediate concern to manufacturers: a
younger member of the family passing his or her driving test. Even among
more affluent families, that usually means the purchase of a used car.
Of those planning to buy new secondary cars, the Lex/MORI report found most
people, 32 per cent, listing increased income making it possible to buy a
car that had long been wanted. Other key reasons included the increased
needs of a growing family (20 per cent), starting a job where a car is
needed (20), moving home to where an additional car is needed more urgently
(20) and even lower car prices (8).
Unlike the 'first' car of more than 3m drivers in the UK - those running
company vehicles - secondary cars are ovewhelmingly a private purchase made
out of individuals' after-tax income.
That, at least, is the evidence provided by the Monks Partnership's annual
survey of UK company car policy**, even though in many larger companies
envy-provoking speculation tends to be commonplace that senior executives
and directors' run spouse's cars 'on the firm' as a matter of course.
The findings of Mr Tony Vernon-Harcourt and his colleagues at Monks are that
such cars remain extremely uncommon even at chief executive and director
level, only three per cent of companies making them available.
With the UK motor industry harbouring growing fears that total new car sales
this year could fail to match even 1991's 1.59m units, nearly one-third down
on the 1989 record of 2.3m, wooing the second car buyer has become a
significant concern for car makers and dealers.
The bad news - for the industry - is that, since government statistics show
four out of ten drivers now to be women, the battle for sales will depend
heavily not on styling, chic or other emotional factors - but on price.
For it is by women that the majority of second cars are driven, and the
industry's market research shows up consistently that three-quarters of them
care little about what car they drive, provided it is relatively small and
gets them from point A to B.
Looking beyond the immediate problems of the recession, however, the
long-term indicators for the growth of the second car market remain
positive.
The hope of the environmental lobby, for example, that increasing congestion
will act as a disincentive to car purchase appears ill-founded, with various
surveys indicating that little more than one in ten drivers would consider
using public transport more. And congested though the UK's roads may appear
to be, the vehicle population per head still has a very long way to go
before it reaches US levels - 602 per 1,000 population - or even German, 492
per 1,000.
Nor does the argument that other countries have many more miles of roads to
drive on. Italy has considerably more cars per head than the UK - 476 per
1,000 - despite a congested 91 cars per kilometre of road compared with only
61 for both the UK and Germany.
*Lex Report on Motoring 1992; available from Lex Service PLC, Lex House, 17
Connaught Place, London W2 2EL; Pounds 175.
**Company Car Policy UK; Monks Partnership, Debden Green, Saffron Walden,
Essex CB11 3LX; Pounds 100.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
