<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUL 92 / The Lex Column: Albert Fisher
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The initial 15 per cent jump in Albert Fisher's share price yesterday might
seem a graceless farewell to the man who built the company's value from
almost zero to nearly Pounds 800m in less than a decade. The snag was, of
course, that Mr Tony Millar then presided over the collapse in its value to
some Pounds 230m in the space of 15 months. Plainly, there is scope for new
management to sort out what lies behind the company's recent history of
spectacular accidents.
But it may not work like that. The new chairman Mr Stephen Walls, recently
deposed from Arjo Wiggins Appleton, evidently has larger ambitions than
running a greengrocer. The day-to-day management of the company is to
devolve to the two divisional chiefs of Europe and North America. There is
talk of a strategic review, involving reshaping the company through
acquisition or disposal. There is no talk at all on the more pressing
question of the final dividend. The company is now drifting in a period of
transition. Given that the previous problem for investors was precisely the
lack of clarity on what was going on, that scarcely seems a recommendation
for the shares.
</TEXT>
