<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Money Markets: No joy in sterling
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POUND may have firmed slightly on the foreign exchanges yesterday, but
sentiment in the sterling money markets remained decidedly bearish.
In the morning, dealers had been nervously expecting sterling to dip below
DM2.83, increasing the chances of another base rate rise to halt the
currency's fall. There was relief to see it peak at DM2.8413 in the
mid-morning, but one dealer put this down to technical factors. 'The Forex
market was caught short of sterling and there was a technical move to get
back into the currency,' he said.
The underlying trend is still gloomy, and many believe that a drop down to
DM2.82 is on the cards. Yesterday's decision by the Bank of Spain to lift
its key interest rate by 60 basis points added to the pressure on the Bank
of England to tighten policy. Dealers did not feel that the UK's decision to
tighten controls on government spending had much impact. 'It is a bit of
good housekeeping and little more,' said one dealer. 'They are not cutting
expenditure, just ensuring that they stay within this year's targets.'
Period rates therefore ended the day a little firmer. One-month money closed
unchanged at 10 3/16 per cent offered. But everything from 3-month money to
1-year rose to 10 3/8 from 10 5/16 per cent.
Trading in sterling futures was a little more bullish than in the cash. But
this was because futures traders took sterling's rise at face value, without
looking at the underlying factors. In the morning the September short
sterling contract dipped six basis points to 89.63 because of currency
fears. But as these evaporated for the day, it shot up to finish at 89.72.
The December contract fell before closing 4 basis points down on the day at
89.96.
The Bank of England forecast another surprisingly low shortage of Pounds
500m in the morning but the market was slow to take it out. The shortages
this week have so far amounted to only Pounds 2.8bn. At the start of the
week, it had looked as though they might amount to Pounds 4.5bn, so a tough
finish may be in store today.
The Bank did not operate in the morning. In the afternoon it purchased
Pounds 144m of Band 1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent and gave late assistance
of Pounds 70m.
</TEXT>
